teams.strTeam: C&L Fairburn Properties -Look Forward Racing Honda
teams.strDescriptionEN:
The C&L Fairburn Properties/Look Forward Racing team will step up to the all-new Bennetts British Superbike Championship in 2024 with Billy McConnell as the team move into the premier class from the Pirelli National Superstock Championship.
Chris Fairburn’s team have quickly established themselves as one of the most professional in the paddock, initially as one of McConnell's personal sponsors and then establishing a team in the Superstock class in 2022,  and will move into Bennetts BSB class with Honda Fireblade machinery.

Northern Ireland based TAS Racing is owned and run by father and son pairing, Hector and Philip Neill. The team, who will run under the SYNETIQ BMW banner in 2021, as BMW Motorrad UK’s Official squad, have signed Andrew Irwin and Danny Buchan to ride the all-new M 1000 RR machinery in the British Superbike Championship – in a season that will see TAS Racing celebrate its 21st Anniversary.
Supersport titles were won in 2007 and 2011 when employing homegrown talent in Michael Laverty and Alastair Seeley, with the diminutive Carrick ace Seeley also collecting the National Superstock crown in 2009. All three titles coming with support from Suzuki GB.
This season TAS Racing are again the officially supported team of BMW Motorrad with SYNETIQ Intelligent Solutions the title partner. Essex ace Danny Buchan and Ulsterman Andrew Irwin remain the two riders who Hector and Philip have pinned their hopes on for success as the next chapter in the long rich history of TAS Racing gets underway.

The FS-3 Racing Kawasaki team, are the official Team Green entry in the Bennetts British Superbike championship,  Keeping with the same exciting line up of Lee Jackson and Rory Skinner, 2022 will be the sixth season that the Coventry-based team has partnered with Kawasaki.

Team IWR made a welcome return to the Bennetts British Superbike Championship grid at Donington Park last year, as they featured on the grid to test the new BSB Pathway specification technical regulations with Alex Olsen for the final two rounds of the season.
IWR were multiple Superbike Cup winners earlier in the team’s history and after recently returning to racing in the Pirelli National Superstock Championship, the team now return to the Superbike class full-time in 2024 with the Honda in the new BSB Pathway specification.

DAO Racing is one of the most iconic motorcycle road racing teams of the current era – and has now also become regular fixture in the Bennetts British Superbike Championship. As reigning 2019 winners of the Isle of Man Senior TT  with rider Dean Harrison, the team embarked on its first full Bennetts BSB season in 2021.
The team began life in 2007 as a leading Supermoto World Championship squad and won 2013 title with Finnish rider Mauno Hermunen before moving into road racing, winning the 2015 Senior Manx GP with the late Malachi Mitchel-Thomas.
As Kawasaki’s official Team Green road racing squad, the team is enjoying the new challenge of being a regular part of the Bennetts British Superbike Championship as it plans its second full season in 2022.

FHO Racing are one of the newest teams in the Bennetts British Superbike Championship, who made their debut in 2021 with a dynamic new look.
After being involved in the sport with rider and team sponsorship for more than five years, securing a huge amount of success accomplishing TT and Macau wins and more, Faye Ho decided to pursue her dream of being a team owner of a professional motorcycle race team.
Equipped with the highly-anticipated BMW M 1000 RR Superbike, the first M model from BMW Motorrad, the FHO Racing Superbike team claimed victories in their debut season and the first podium finish in Bennetts BSB for the 'M' model.

A former Grand Prix motocross rider until injury forced him to retire; Paul Bird started helping local riders back in the early 90s before starting his own team in 1996. For the next decade, Paul Bird Motorsport established itself as one of the leading teams in both the British Championships and on the roads culminating in nine domestic titles as well as two prestigious Isle of Man TT victories.
Bird’s team has a strong pedigree having won consecutive British Superbike Championship titles, first through the late, legendary Steve Hislop in 2002 and then Shane ‘Shakey’ Byrne a year later, with Stuart Easton also winning the Supersport title to add to John McGuinness’ 250cc crown of 1999. 
Based in Langwathby in Cumbria, Paul Bird’s global motorsport operation combines motorsport on both two wheels and four. In addition to two-wheel competition, his son Frank Bird will continue his racing career in the GT World Challenge Europe Endurance & Sprint Cup as part of Team WRT in a factory-supported Audi

Honda UK has a strong history in the Bennetts British Superbike Championship, securing four Superbike titles, making them one of the most successful teams in the paddock.
Ryuichi Kiyonari won the Louth-based team consecutive Championship titles in 2006 and 2007, before following them up in 2010 and with Alex Lowes in 2013. The team has also won three British Supersport and National Superstock crowns, including last year with Tom Neave.
As part of the ‘Honda Superbike Challenge Program’, Honda Racing UK signed Japanese contenders Ryo Mizuno and Takumi Takahashi alongside Glenn Irwin. The trio return in 2022 with the team’s Superstock champion Tom Neave promoted to the Superbike class in an ambitious four-strong line-up for the new season.

The team has been a regular competitor in the National Superstock Championship in recent years, notching up a number of strong overall results with its Aprilia package via the likes of Rollo, Tom Ward and Fraser Rogers.
This year, however, will see IN Competition SENCAT make the full-time move into BSB for 2024 under the new ‘Pathway’ regulations designed to ease the transition from Superstock to Superbike-spec machinery.

teams.strTeamAlternate: Team LKQ Euro Car Parts Kawasaki
teams.strDescriptionEN:
GR Motosport was formed in 1995 and the Sheffield based team celebrated their 25th anniversary season last year as they continue to promote young riders with the Bennetts British Superbike Championship and its support classes.
Owned by Brent Gladwin, when injury ended his riding career, the team have scored a European and eight British titles, including the 2016 British Supersport Championship with Tarran Mackenzie.
LKQ Euro Car Parts has extended its title partnership with Kawasaki for the next Bennetts British Superbike Championship - the leading road racing superbike championship in the UK.
The partnership known as Team LKQ Euro Car Parts Kawasaki has also announced it has re-signed rider Storm Stacey for the 2022 season.

Hawk Racing was founded by Team Principal Stuart Hicken in 1996.  Since its inception Hawk Racing has grown from a one-rider 600 Supersport team to become Suzuki’s official entry in the Bennetts British Superbike Championship (BSB), based at Mallory Park circuit in Leicestershire.
The team is now managed by Stuart's son Steve, who not only runs the team, but is also a hands on crew chief, working at the heart of the Buildbase Suzuki pit box.

McAMS Yamaha is the latest title for the Raceways Motorcycles team which has competed at various levels of motorcycle racing, both internationally and nationally, over the last 30 years.
Raceways racing pedigree includes victories across the board, from the British 125cc championship to British Supersport and most lately the British Superbike class, where in 2021 they notched up their 50th BSB podium and first BSB title victory in just five years in the championship. 
The Fleetwood-based squad had their strongest campaign in the championship to date last year onboard the new-for-2020 YZF-R1. Mackenzie secured the title victory at the season finale, whilst O’Halloran claimed third place in the final standings and the line up remains unchanged for 2022.
Raceways Motorcycles, the team behind McAMS Yamaha is based at the Fleetwood Yamaha dealership – Raceways Motorcycles.

NP Motorcycles have been involved in racing and within the Bennetts British Superbike Championship since 2004, however 2020 was their debut season in the premier class.
They began their debut campaign with Bjorn Estment before ending the season with Lachlan Epis at the final round at Brands Hatch, before Joey Thompson joined the team in 2021. The team now return with Louis Valleley as he prepares for his first full season in Bennetts BSB.

Formed in 2018, OMG Racing are a prominent team within elite tier motorcycle racing. The team took victory in last year’s Bennetts British Superbike Championship, the world’s most popular domestic motorcycle series, with more race wins than anyone on the grid during the season, as well as making their debut in the world-famous Isle of Man TT with James Hillier, one of the 10 Fastest riders ever around the circuit. In 2023, OMG Racing aim to retain their BSB title with 2022 rider Kyle Ryde, and 2018 Junior Superstock Champion Ryan Vickers.

Moto Rapido Racing is owned by Steve Moore and the team are based at their Ducati dealership in Winchester.  The team moved to national level racing in 2009 when Scott Smart joined them to race the Ducati 1198 in the Superstock 1000 class, before moving into the Superbike Evo class in 2011.
Bridewell joined the Winchester-based team midway through the 2018 season and since joining forces, together they have celebrated race wins and podiums, with their strongest finish in 2019, when they ended the season in third place in the title fight.
Bridewell’s return to Moto Rapido Racing in 2022 followed the announcement that the team extended their title partnership agreement with Oxford Products for a further two years into the 2022 season.

The Marvel HCL Motorsport team step up to the Bennetts British Superbike Championship full-time this year after making their debut in the final two rounds of the 2023 season as the Pirelli National Superstock podium finishers line up with returning Franco Bourne on a Pathway specification Honda CBR1000RR-R Fireblade SP.
The Marvel HCL Motorsport team together with Bourne had a strong start to the 2023 season in the Superstock class, claiming three podium finishes including a victory. Bourne then made his Bennetts BSB debut when he deputised for Andrew Irwin at Honda Racing UK when he was injured during a test at Knockhill.
Bourne gained vital experience with the Honda Racing UK team, scoring points whilst continuing learning in the Superbike class and now he is ready for his first full season as he is reunited with his Marvel HCL Motorsport team with title sponsorship from Rapid Training, who continue to have a strong presence in the Championship.

GR Motosport expands to a two-rider team for the forthcoming season as Tom Neave joins the Sheffield-based contenders on the STAUFF Fluid Power Kawasaki.
GR Motosport and STAUFF UK  have celebrated title victories in both the British Moto3 and Quattro Group British Supersport Championships, with the STAUFF team most recently competing in the Pirelli National Superstock Championship.

TAG Racing made their debut in the Bennetts British Superbike Championship in 2014 as they progressed to the premier class following five successful seasons competing in the British Supersport Championship. The team scored a podium finish at Brands Hatch with Richard Cooper in 2015 and over the winter switched to the Yamaha YZF-R1 for the 2016 season.
TAG Racing became an official Honda Racing UK supported team, with Linfoot aiming for success on the new Honda CBR1000RR-R Fireblade SP, but it was a tough campaign before Luke Mossey lined up with TAG Racing at the season finale, claiming pole position. Race winner and Showdown contender Mossey remains with the team in 2022.
CDH Racing has announced a new partnership with Whiteclife Electrical Distribution ahead of the 2024 Bennetts British Superbike Championship season.
